
[1]seethe

   SEETHE, v. t. pret. seethed, sod; pp. seethed, sodden. [Heb. to seethe,
   to boil, to swell, to be inflated.] To boil; to decoct or prepare for
   food in hot liquor; as, to seethe flesh.

   Thou shalt not seethe a kid in its mother's milk. Ex. 23.

   SEETHE, v. i. To be in a state of ebullition; to be hot. [This word is
   rarely used in the common concerns of life.]
